powerful legal documents,

00:00:59.240 --> 00:01:01.270
one of the most durable.

00:01:01.270 --> 00:01:03.700
It has qualities
that make it last.

00:01:03.700 --> 00:01:06.610
But it also has the
ability to change.

00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:08.920
And the way that the
Constitution changes--

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:11.530
you know, one is through
the formal amendments.

00:01:11.530 --> 00:01:13.990
But it's also in the
way that the people

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:16.840
embrace the Constitution--
whether we defend it,

00:01:16.840 --> 00:01:21.250
whether we stand for it, whether
we apply its principles fully,

00:01:21.250 --> 00:01:24.490
or whether we step back from
it and let it be taken from us

00:01:24.490 --> 00:01:27.160
or used against people's rights.

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:31.540
So the original Constitution
of the United States

00:01:31.540 --> 00:01:35.050
basically created the separation
of powers between the Executive

00:01:35.050 --> 00:01:38.920
Branch, Congress, the
Judiciary, and then

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:42.400
the basic structure of
federalism with the states.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:46.060
But the Constitution originally
had very few protections

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:50.350
for individual
rights, and those were

00:01:50.350 --> 00:01:52.840
enacted through the
first 10 Amendments

00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:56.140
to the Constitution, which
we call the Bill of Rights.

00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:59.830
So when you think about the
Constitutional amendments,

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:02.590
I think the Second Amendment
is obviously very famous.

00:02:02.590 --> 00:02:04.280
It's always in the news.

00:02:04.280 --> 00:02:06.190
People can associate
the Second Amendment

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:09.310
with whether it's collective
or an individual right

00:02:09.310 --> 00:02:10.840
to bear arms.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:14.290
The First Amendment also gets
a certain amount of attention,

00:02:14.290 --> 00:02:16.540
and rightly so.

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:19.000
When people ask me what's
my favorite Amendment

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.950
of the Constitution,
though, my answer

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:24.760
is the 14th Amendment
of the Constitution.

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:27.350
The 14th Amendment
does a few things.

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:31.360
First, it says that all
persons born or naturalized

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:34.690
in the United States and
subject to the jurisdiction

00:02:34.690 --> 00:02:40.720
thereof are citizens of the
United States and of the state

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:43.390
wherein they reside.

00:02:43.390 --> 00:02:46.150
That's a profoundly
important sentence.

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:49.090
What it says is that there's
two paths to citizenship--

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:51.910
citizenship by birth
and citizenship

00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:55.430
through the naturalization
or immigration process.

00:02:55.430 --> 00:02:58.150
The reason the 14th Amendment
is my favorite amendment

00:02:58.150 --> 00:03:00.970
is that I am a
citizen because of it.

00:03:00.970 --> 00:03:03.160
I was born in this country--

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:05.770
when my parents are
both from Iran--

00:03:05.770 --> 00:03:08.080
I was born in this
country in 1973.

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:10.840
And that's what
made me a citizen.

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:13.540
Because of the fact that
my parents were Iranians,

00:03:13.540 --> 00:03:16.870
I associate my citizenship very
squarely with this Amendment

00:03:16.870 --> 00:03:18.440
of the Constitution.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:22.290
But every one of us who is a
citizen, every last person who

00:03:22.290 --> 00:03:25.090
is a citizen, it's
either by birth

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:27.630
or through naturalization.

00:03:27.630 --> 00:03:31.770
So the 14th Amendment,
that's one core plank.

00:03:31.770 --> 00:03:36.000
After that, it goes on
to say that no state can

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.690
deny the privileges or
immunities of a citizen

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:41.940
of the United States.

00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:44.310
And then, from there
it goes on, and it

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:48.690
changes from talking
about citizen to person.

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:54.080
And it says that no state can
deny to any person due process

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.610
under the law.

00:03:55.610 --> 00:03:58.940
And that no state can
deny to any person

00:03:58.940 --> 00:04:02.690
the equal protection of the law.

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:05.690
So the people who wrote
the 14th Amendment

00:04:05.690 --> 00:04:09.140
did so in the aftermath
of abolishing slavery

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:11.220
in the United States.

00:04:11.220 --> 00:04:15.140
The 13th Amendment that
immediately precedes the 14th

00:04:15.140 --> 00:04:17.399
abolished slavery.

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:19.110
And at that time, the
thought was, well,

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:22.320
if you abolished slavery,
well, then, by definition,

00:04:22.320 --> 00:04:25.080
the people who are
freed from slavery

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:29.190
should be treated equally as
human beings and as citizens.

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:32.790
But immediately, the states
that had slavery, as well

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:36.450
as the northern states,
set about a set of policies

00:04:36.450 --> 00:04:40.180
to discriminate against
free black people.

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:43.740
And so the 14th Amendment
was necessary to make clear

00:04:43.740 --> 00:04:48.060
that every person born here is a
citizen, that no state can take

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:50.920
away the rights of a citizen.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:54.180
But then they switched from
talking only about citizens

00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:56.700
to also talking
about persons, when

00:04:56.700 --> 00:04:58.560
they said that every
person is entitled

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:01.550
to due process and
equal protection.

00:05:01.550 --> 00:05:04.670
So why would they,
in crafting Section I

00:05:04.670 --> 00:05:08.990
of the 14th Amendment, talk
about citizens and persons

00:05:08.990 --> 00:05:10.520
so clearly?

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:12.860
It's because they
wanted the Constitution

00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:15.230
to be abundantly clear--

00:05:15.230 --> 00:05:17.720
that it applies on
the fundamental rights

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:21.770
of due process and equality
to every person, citizen

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:24.260
and non-citizen alike.

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:26.870
So I love the 14th Amendment.

00:05:26.870 --> 00:05:30.110
I love it because it was the
path to my own citizenship,

00:05:30.110 --> 00:05:33.830
but also because it marks
this country's progress

00:05:33.830 --> 00:05:36.800
in the abolition of slavery
and the extension of rights

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:40.650
to every citizen
and to every person.

