It was also backed by violence--

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:03.910
through widespread violence,
fear and intimidation

00:14:03.910 --> 00:14:08.320
against black people,
as well as whites

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:10.330
who were involved in
voter registration

00:14:10.330 --> 00:14:12.400
or on the side of
equality, as well.

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:14.440
Although the magnitude
of the attack was most

00:14:14.440 --> 00:14:17.640
pronounced against
African-Americans.

00:14:17.640 --> 00:14:21.480
That period of Jim Crow,
or legalized segregation,

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:23.730
lasted for a very long
time until the Civil Rights

00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:25.510
movement.

00:14:25.510 --> 00:14:29.070
So I think we have to look
at the long arc of the United

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:30.600
States.

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:34.170
The American Revolution,
the original Constitution,

00:14:34.170 --> 00:14:35.520
the Bill of Rights--

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:37.860
they are profoundly
important advances

00:14:37.860 --> 00:14:41.280
for human liberty and
equality, the struggle

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:45.770
to abolish slavery, the
period of Reconstruction.

00:14:45.770 --> 00:14:49.020
The movement to secure the
right to vote for women--

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:52.110
it's one of the longest
movements if you look

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:56.850
at the duration of time that
it took from the time that we

00:14:56.850 --> 00:15:01.080
secured the 15th Amendment,
which protects the right

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:04.140
to vote regardless of race--
the 15th Amendment was one

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:07.530
of the three
post-slavery amendments--

00:15:07.530 --> 00:15:09.870
that was adopted in 1870.

00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:13.980
It took another 50
years, until 1920,

00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:16.740
when the 19th Amendment
protected the right

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:19.380
to vote regardless of sex.

00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:21.780
So I think we have to
take a bit of a long view

00:15:21.780 --> 00:15:22.830
of American history.

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:25.410
We are in a period where a
lot of fundamental rights

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:26.790
are under attack.

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:28.530
We've been through that before.

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:30.990
And the only way we've
gotten through it

00:15:30.990 --> 00:15:34.710
is by every person standing
up on the side of equality

00:15:34.710 --> 00:15:37.260
and freedom and justice
and using their voice

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:40.250
for those enduring values.

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:42.810
SPEAKER 1: Thank you so much.

00:15:42.810 --> 00:15:47.850
Now going back to the discussion
that we started on travel ban,

00:15:47.850 --> 00:15:50.010
and later on, I guess,
family separation falls

00:15:50.010 --> 00:15:55.020
into the same category,
we saw extreme support

00:15:55.020 --> 00:15:59.460
from people who thought
that this is unjust.

00:15:59.460 --> 00:16:02.320
This shouldn't be happening.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:06.020
People are going to
airport, very heartwarming.

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:08.590
Although the family
separation issue is ongoing,

00:16:08.590 --> 00:16:13.320
we just recently heard that
another 1,500 cases of kids

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:18.607
that were put under care,
as their cases are missing,

00:16:18.607 --> 00:16:20.190
and they cannot be
tracked, and so on.

00:16:20.190 --> 00:16:21.930
So that issue is ongoing.

00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:23.670
But the point that
I want to get to

00:16:23.670 --> 00:16:28.260
is that there was this
political atmosphere that

00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:33.330
allowed these two rather
cruel acts to go into effect.

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:38.880
A few years ago, like,
probably, five, 10 years ago,

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:41.420
it would have been unimaginable,
things like this happening.

00:16:41.420 --> 00:16:43.910
Like, singling out
Muslims, or separating

00:16:43.910 --> 00:16:48.840
children from their families in
the way it happened and so on.

00:16:48.840 --> 00:16:51.530
What happened in our
political atmosphere that

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:54.110
allowed for things like
this to actually happen

00:16:54.110 --> 00:16:55.251
in the first place?

00:16:55.251 --> 00:16:57.500
So what was the root cause,
and how can we prevent it?

00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:00.440
How can we address the root
causes of this situation,

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:04.339
of anything like this
being even accepted?

00:17:04.339 --> 00:17:07.819
ABDI SOLTANI: You know, I think
that there's maybe, like--

00:17:07.819 --> 00:17:09.589
I'm going to simplify
this a little bit,

00:17:09.589 --> 00:17:11.960
but maybe two
categories of people.

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:13.490
There's the category
of people who

00:17:13.490 --> 00:17:17.030
after Trump won, woke up
and were kind of shocked

00:17:17.030 --> 00:17:18.260
that this could happen.

00:17:18.260 --> 00:17:20.599
You know, like, how
is it even possible

00:17:20.599 --> 00:17:22.970
that a person who says
the things they do

00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:24.784
could win the election?

00:17:24.784 --> 00:17:26.200
And then there's
a second category

00:17:26.200 --> 00:17:29.200
of people who've been actually
dealing with and facing

00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:32.110
pretty deep-seated
discrimination in the United

00:17:32.110 --> 00:17:35.260
States that has
had very deep roots

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:39.130
and for whom this was
actually the manifestation

00:17:39.130 --> 00:17:44.410
of that exact existing
set of problems.

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:47.030
I think whichever
way one looks at it,

00:17:47.030 --> 00:17:51.400
the current situation,
in terms of the policies

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:55.660
of this administration,
are at a different level

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:58.930
in terms of their
cruelty, in terms

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:04.400
of how patently they are
designed to carry out

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:07.130
a policy of exclusion.

00:18:07.130 --> 00:18:08.890
Going back to the
14th Amendment,

00:18:08.890 --> 00:18:11.970
of which I'm very fond--

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:15.860
you know the 14th Amendment
is a chain of words

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:20.090
that says all persons born
or naturalized in the United

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:24.440
States and subject to the
jurisdiction thereof are

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:28.600
citizens of the United States
and of the state wherein

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:30.670
they reside.

00:18:30.670 --> 00:18:36.960
This sentence represents a
path from person to citizen.

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:39.350
And I think that we have
to be very clear eyed,

00:18:39.350 --> 00:18:41.690
that the totality
of the policies

00:18:41.690 --> 00:18:46.550
of the current administration
is to stop every possible point

00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:47.210
in that path.

00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:53.030
So it includes the
mass deportation

00:18:53.030 --> 00:18:57.010
of undocumented immigrants
without due process.

00:18:57.010 --> 00:18:59.730
It includes reducing
dramatically the number

00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:02.790
of refugees that the
United States will

00:19:02.790 --> 00:19:05.320
permit to come to the country.

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:10.990
A new policy that we have seen
through leaked news reports

00:19:10.990 --> 00:19:13.930
is this idea of public charge.

00:19:13.930 --> 00:19:16.390
Historically, the United
States would deny a path

00:19:16.390 --> 00:19:20.500
to citizenship for a person
who was institutionalized

00:19:20.500 --> 00:19:22.420
in the care of the government.

00:19:22.420 --> 00:19:24.160
The idea was that you
have to be somewhat

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:27.280
self-sufficient to be able to
get through the immigration

00:19:27.280 --> 00:19:28.720
process.

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:30.970
They now want to
change that definition

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:33.610
to include just
about anybody who

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:38.630
has received any form of
services from the government.

00:19:38.630 --> 00:19:40.990
So that's another
attempt to limit

00:19:40.990 --> 00:19:44.800
that path to legal immigration.

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:50.820
So I think that that's a major
cumulative set of policies

00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:55.230
that's designed to keep the
United States demographically

00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:59.910
from changing and its intended
purpose is to keep people out--

00:19:59.910 --> 00:20:04.570
and very much from Latin
America, Central America,

00:20:04.570 --> 00:20:06.780
Africa, Asia, et cetera.

00:20:06.780 --> 00:20:08.730
The idea of family--

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:12.870
chain migration, which
they are also focusing on,

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:15.330
has been the main vehicle
through which Asian-Americans

00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:17.760
have immigrated to
the United States.

00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:21.210
There's really nobody who
is immune to these policies

00:20:21.210 --> 00:20:23.610
of exclusion.

00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:25.890
At the same time,
there's a set of policies

00:20:25.890 --> 00:20:28.710
that are aimed at
the rules of the game

00:20:28.710 --> 00:20:32.530
and the way in which power
itself is distributed.

00:20:32.530 --> 00:20:36.120
So the attack on the right to
vote with the concerted efforts

00:20:36.120 --> 00:20:40.530
at voter suppression, the
political gerrymandering

00:20:40.530 --> 00:20:45.120
of districts so that it reduces
the influence of each voter

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:49.250
in their state or federal
government, the inclusion

00:20:49.250 --> 00:20:53.180
of the question about
citizenship in the census

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:55.040
that has the intended
effect both of

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:58.280
intimidating people
from taking the census,

00:20:58.280 --> 00:21:01.310
but also of creating the record
by which then the government

00:21:01.310 --> 00:21:05.510
can allocate differentially
certain benefits by population

00:21:05.510 --> 00:21:08.150
according to citizen,
instead of according

00:21:08.150 --> 00:21:11.620
to the number of persons.

00:21:11.620 --> 00:21:13.530
So this is all very serious.

00:21:13.530 --> 00:21:16.890
And I think that we
have to be involved

00:21:16.890 --> 00:21:20.770
in speaking up for basic
principles of equality,

00:21:20.770 --> 00:21:23.940
fairness, and freedom.

00:21:23.940 --> 00:21:27.770
So the 14th Amendment, you know,
how it itself plays into it

00:21:27.770 --> 00:21:31.640
is very much at the center
of a lot of these debates.

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:34.550
The equal protection
of the law--

00:21:34.550 --> 00:21:37.480
well, who does that apply to?

00:21:37.480 --> 00:21:40.360
Those words, equal
protection of the law,

00:21:40.360 --> 00:21:42.940
did not make it into
the Constitution

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:45.700
until the 14th Amendment.

00:21:45.700 --> 00:21:47.650
Those are the words
based on which

00:21:47.650 --> 00:21:52.090
we've made a lot of the gains
for lesbian and gay couples

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:55.660
to have equal access to
marriage or to other government

00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:57.100
benefits.

00:21:57.100 --> 00:22:00.490
So our view is that that
principle of equal protection

00:22:00.490 --> 00:22:03.370
needs to be robust
and inclusive,

00:22:03.370 --> 00:22:08.250
and it needs to be a force
to combat discrimination.

00:22:08.250 --> 00:22:12.240
Other people can view equal
protection very narrowly

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:14.712
and try to limit
its application.

00:22:14.712 --> 00:22:16.170
And so that's going
to be something

00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:21.640
that gets fought in the Supreme
Court in the coming decades.

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:24.172
SPEAKER 1: So I
want to move to some

00:22:24.172 --> 00:22:27.850
of the topics that are more
related to practical aspects

00:22:27.850 --> 00:22:28.900
of ACLU's work.

00:22:28.900 --> 00:22:32.810
So we've heard about People
Power, the grassroots efforts

00:22:32.810 --> 00:22:36.400
that ACLU is instantiating
