00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:38.700
Can you tell us a little
bit about People Power,

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:41.970
and what are the ambitions, what
are the goals and objectives--

00:22:41.970 --> 00:22:44.910
where we are, and
how we can help.

00:22:44.910 --> 00:22:48.510
ABDI SOLTANI: So I spoke before
about the 14th Amendment.

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:51.120
But I also want people to know
I'm a big fan of the First

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:52.610
Amendment.

00:22:52.610 --> 00:22:55.020
And you can think about
the First Amendment

00:22:55.020 --> 00:22:57.990
as something that's
a legal protection.

00:22:57.990 --> 00:23:01.860
But it's actually an incredibly
beautiful and poetic.

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:03.330
And if you haven't
taken the time

00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:05.040
to read the First
Amendment recently,

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:07.050
I'd really encourage you to.

00:23:07.050 --> 00:23:10.260
It says that Congress
shall pass no law abridging

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:14.270
the freedom of religion
or to establish religion,

00:23:14.270 --> 00:23:18.810
that Congress can pass no law
limiting the freedom of speech,

00:23:18.810 --> 00:23:21.990
or the right of the people
to peaceably assemble,

00:23:21.990 --> 00:23:25.830
or the right and the
freedom of the press.

00:23:25.830 --> 00:23:29.830
And then the First
Amendment culminates in that

00:23:29.830 --> 00:23:34.000
the government cannot
limit our right to petition

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:38.100
the government for a
redress of grievances.

00:23:38.100 --> 00:23:40.490
So when you read the First
Amendment as a whole.

00:23:40.490 --> 00:23:45.170
it begins from the place of our
inner beliefs and our values--

00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:47.720
both the idea that the
government cannot tell you

00:23:47.720 --> 00:23:50.600
your religion nor can
the government deny you

00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:51.980
your religion.

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:54.620
And the case on
the First Amendment

00:23:54.620 --> 00:23:57.350
has evolved to be clear
that religion includes

00:23:57.350 --> 00:23:59.360
your conscience,
in many instances,

00:23:59.360 --> 00:24:03.230
like your secular beliefs
that are deeply held.

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:05.870
And then from there, it goes
to your freedom of speech

00:24:05.870 --> 00:24:09.590
and of the press and your
power to assemble as a group,

00:24:09.590 --> 00:24:13.440
and then petition the government
for a redress of grievances.

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:15.410
So it's a chain
from your beliefs

00:24:15.410 --> 00:24:17.930
to your relationship
to government.

00:24:17.930 --> 00:24:20.780
And this is a very simple
point that I'm making.

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:25.040
There's a beautiful book written
called "Madison's Music."

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:27.020
It's about looking at
the First Amendment

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:29.880
as a holistic principle.

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:34.950
So to your question about People
Power, our view at the ACLU

00:24:34.950 --> 00:24:38.490
is that the kinds of assaults
that we're facing on our rights

00:24:38.490 --> 00:24:42.870
are not ones that we can
secure only through the courts.

00:24:42.870 --> 00:24:46.650
They require the
participation of people

00:24:46.650 --> 00:24:49.680
in the exercise of
their freedom of speech,

00:24:49.680 --> 00:24:52.800
in their assembling
together peacefully,

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:54.930
and in petitioning
the government.

00:24:54.930 --> 00:24:57.660
That is the First
Amendment itself.

00:24:57.660 --> 00:25:02.370
So PeoplePower.org is
a new flank of the ACLU

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:06.300
that's an online platform
that allows people to organize

00:25:06.300 --> 00:25:09.990
in defense of their liberties,
in defense of equality,

00:25:09.990 --> 00:25:12.810
in association with the ACLU.

00:25:12.810 --> 00:25:15.910
And for us, as a long
time legal organization,

00:25:15.910 --> 00:25:17.850
this was a recognition
that, while we're

00:25:17.850 --> 00:25:20.010
going to continue
to go to court,

00:25:20.010 --> 00:25:23.670
the ultimate defense of
liberty is people's involvement

00:25:23.670 --> 00:25:25.620
exercising their
First Amendment rights

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:30.055
through organized campaigns like
we offer on PeoplePower.org.

00:25:30.055 --> 00:25:30.930
SPEAKER 1: Very well.

00:25:30.930 --> 00:25:31.840
Thank you.

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:33.450
So you mentioned
First Amendment.

00:25:33.450 --> 00:25:36.139
And I want to ask a question
that is a little bit related

00:25:36.139 --> 00:25:36.930
to First Amendment.

00:25:36.930 --> 00:25:41.390
So this is a discussion that
these days is being discussed

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:45.480
in the media to some extent.

00:25:45.480 --> 00:25:49.290
Some people are worried
about giving platforms,

00:25:49.290 --> 00:25:53.550
unintentionally giving
platform, to hateful speech.

00:25:53.550 --> 00:25:57.390
But this is not the first
time that hateful speech

00:25:57.390 --> 00:25:58.460
is appearing.

00:25:58.460 --> 00:26:01.290
The incident of William
Shockley and Yale University

00:26:01.290 --> 00:26:04.500
from the 70s, that's
a very famous one.

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:07.090
What happened afterwards,
there was this postmortem,

00:26:07.090 --> 00:26:10.770
this discussion of what
are the boundaries, what

00:26:10.770 --> 00:26:14.830
are the sort of speech that we
have to allow to take place.

00:26:14.830 --> 00:26:17.220
And we know that the ACLU
has been on forefront

00:26:17.220 --> 00:26:20.500
of defending First Amendment.

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:21.690
What are your advices?

00:26:21.690 --> 00:26:25.530
What are your
thoughts or mindset

00:26:25.530 --> 00:26:29.090
on how we should
set the boundary,

00:26:29.090 --> 00:26:34.470
where should we draw the line
between speech that is not

00:26:34.470 --> 00:26:36.360
going to be tolerated
and something

00:26:36.360 --> 00:26:38.164
that has to be tolerated,
no matter what?

00:26:38.164 --> 00:26:39.080
Where is the boundary?

00:26:39.080 --> 00:26:41.170
What is a guideline?

00:26:41.170 --> 00:26:43.270
ABDI SOLTANI: So this
is a great question,

00:26:43.270 --> 00:26:48.120
and one that is the subject of
a great deal of legal thought,

00:26:48.120 --> 00:26:51.240
social science thought, and
people's own conversations

00:26:51.240 --> 00:26:53.880
about what is that line.

00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:57.090
I think the basic
principle of the ACLU

00:26:57.090 --> 00:27:01.440
is that we do not want to give
that power to the government

00:27:01.440 --> 00:27:06.090
to decide who can say what
and when they can say it.

00:27:06.090 --> 00:27:09.510
One of the earliest, and
one of the famous cases

00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:12.240
that the ACLU brought here
in Northern California,

00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:17.040
was the case in a poem called
"Howl" by Allen Ginsberg.

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.850
So if anyone goes to North Beach
neighborhood in San Francisco,

00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:23.160
you'll come across
City Lights Bookstore.

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:24.650
And they were the publisher--

00:27:24.650 --> 00:27:27.720
with Lawrence Ferlinghetti--
the publisher of Allen Ginsberg,

00:27:27.720 --> 00:27:31.830
the poet of this beautiful
poem called "Howl."

00:27:31.830 --> 00:27:34.260
The poem talks about gay sex.

00:27:34.260 --> 00:27:36.120
It talks about drug use.

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:38.130
It talks about depression.

00:27:38.130 --> 00:27:43.800
And those things were considered
offensive and obscene.

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:47.100
And for that reason,
that poem was censored,

00:27:47.100 --> 00:27:50.430
I believe, by the postal service
that wouldn't distribute it.

00:27:50.430 --> 00:27:51.580
So we went to court.

00:27:51.580 --> 00:27:52.970
This is the 1950s.

00:27:52.970 --> 00:27:56.640
And won a ruling on the side
that this poem can and should

00:27:56.640 --> 00:27:59.790
be published and the government
cannot censor something

00:27:59.790 --> 00:28:03.660
because someone
considers it obscene.

00:28:03.660 --> 00:28:07.350
I think as time has
passed, a lot of people

00:28:07.350 --> 00:28:09.510
have kind of lost track of that.

00:28:09.510 --> 00:28:11.460
And there's a sense
that if there's

00:28:11.460 --> 00:28:13.140
language that's
hateful, if there's

00:28:13.140 --> 00:28:16.230
language that's discriminatory,
that we should give

00:28:16.230 --> 00:28:19.260
the government the power,
in one form or another,

00:28:19.260 --> 00:28:22.000
to limit the expression
of that view.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.840
And the ACLU-- we still
stand by the principle

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:28.980
that that would be a really
dangerous path to go down.

00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:31.270
It is dangerous for
a number of reasons.

00:28:31.270 --> 00:28:34.140
One is that we don't believe
that force or government

00:28:34.140 --> 00:28:37.440
power should be used to suppress
the ability of a human being

00:28:37.440 --> 00:28:40.000
to express a point of view.

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:44.160
Beyond that, once you create
that basis and legal precedent,

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:47.800
or in other places, that
will be used in all manner

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:51.100
to restrict all forms of
expression that someone

00:28:51.100 --> 00:28:55.480
finds offensive, or
discriminatory, or the like.

00:28:55.480 --> 00:28:57.970
Now what are the limits to that?

00:28:57.970 --> 00:29:01.660
One is the limit of
a threat of violence.

00:29:01.660 --> 00:29:03.700
If there's a
statement that is made

00:29:03.700 --> 00:29:07.930
that's targeted an individual,
and it's a threat of violence,

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:09.730
that's different.

00:29:09.730 --> 00:29:12.850
Another would be, like, sexual
harassment or racial harassment

00:29:12.850 --> 00:29:16.480
in the workplace or in a school,
where a person should have

00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:19.510
the right to free
employment and education,

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:21.010
free from discrimination.

00:29:21.010 --> 00:29:23.980
So there are places where
there's a limit to it.

00:29:23.980 --> 00:29:26.160
You know, Google being
a technology company,

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:29.170
one of the big challenges
is on platforms like YouTube

00:29:29.170 --> 00:29:31.420
or social media
platforms, which is

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:34.480
an inordinately complex area.

00:29:34.480 --> 00:29:37.390
But we're mindful of
how do you make sure

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:40.180
that you don't hand that
power to large corporations

00:29:40.180 --> 00:29:42.400
to then be the deciders
of what can be said

00:29:42.400 --> 00:29:44.350
and what can't be said.

00:29:44.350 --> 00:29:48.640
But some of this language does
cross the line into threats.

00:29:48.640 --> 00:29:49.930
And so how do you manage that?

00:29:49.930 --> 00:29:53.650
That's the problem that the
ACLU is concerned about and one

00:29:53.650 --> 00:29:56.570
that I know companies
are also dealing with.

00:29:56.570 --> 00:30:00.940
SPEAKER 1: So what are the
dangers of overreaction here?

00:30:00.940 --> 00:30:03.610
So that's something that we
see on the progressive side,

00:30:03.610 --> 00:30:06.220
people, like, being
really worried.

00:30:06.220 --> 00:30:09.640
Are you yourself worried?

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:12.930
Is there any sort of advice
that we can make to people who--

00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:14.812
may be studying about past?

00:30:14.812 --> 00:30:16.270
Because this is
not the first time,

00:30:16.270 --> 00:30:18.640
this isn't the first episode
of things like this happening.

00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:20.014
ABDI SOLTANI: You
know, my advice

00:30:20.014 --> 00:30:24.160
would be let's say there's a
speaker who has been invited

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:26.590
to come to a university.

00:30:26.590 --> 00:30:30.070
And there's a group of
people who object strongly

00:30:30.070 --> 00:30:33.640
to the points of view that that
person has expressed before.

00:30:33.640 --> 00:30:38.020
It is equally a freedom of
speech of those protesters

00:30:38.020 --> 00:30:41.000
to protest that
speaker's coming.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:43.550
At the same time, you can
also just ignore the person

00:30:43.550 --> 00:30:46.370
and not give them the
platform of the conflict

00:30:46.370 --> 00:30:48.810
that they're also looking for.

00:30:48.810 --> 00:30:51.470
But I would just
say that I don't

00:30:51.470 --> 00:30:56.780
think it's wise to try
to shut down the speaker

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:00.170
and to use the protest for
the purpose of shutting down

00:31:00.170 --> 00:31:01.370
the speaker.

00:31:01.370 --> 00:31:05.150
I think that that goes
really into an area that's

00:31:05.150 --> 00:31:09.380
not within the realm
of a free society.

00:31:09.380 --> 00:31:11.750
And as satisfying
as that might be,

00:31:11.750 --> 00:31:13.700
the way that that
plays out over time,

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:16.280
it does not lead to
a good destination.

00:31:16.280 --> 00:31:18.710
Someone might say, well, giving
these people the platform

00:31:18.710 --> 00:31:22.020
to speak will also not
lead to a good destination.

00:31:22.020 --> 00:31:23.960
But I think we have
to be wise in how

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:26.600
do we make the choices
about how we protest,

00:31:26.600 --> 00:31:29.270
how we exercise our
freedom of speech

00:31:29.270 --> 00:31:32.260
to lead us down a path towards
actual freedom and actually

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:33.840
equality.

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:37.620
So when a person
is coming to speak,

00:31:37.620 --> 00:31:39.680
and if you object to
what they have to say,

00:31:39.680 --> 00:31:44.340
you can exercise your
freedom of speech vigorously,

00:31:44.340 --> 00:31:46.440
and you can protest
it, and that, too,

00:31:46.440 --> 00:31:48.330
is the freedom of speech.

00:31:48.330 --> 00:31:50.280
But I would just
say where it crosses

00:31:50.280 --> 00:31:54.150
a line is where we expect
government authorities to be

00:31:54.150 --> 00:31:58.800
the ones to censor
someone or where

00:31:58.800 --> 00:32:04.090
we use our protests in order
to shut other people down.

00:32:04.090 --> 00:32:06.395
I think that's a line
that's not worth crossing--

00:32:06.395 --> 00:32:07.270
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:07.769
So--

00:32:07.769 --> 00:32:10.234
ABDI SOLTANI: --or even
appropriate to cross.

00:32:10.234 --> 00:32:11.900
SPEAKER 1: ACLU of
Northern California--

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:15.820
I want to talk about some
California-specific issues.

00:32:15.820 --> 00:32:17.620
In particular,
criminal justice reform

00:32:17.620 --> 00:32:21.520
is one of the areas of interest
that you have been, yourself,

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:24.010
very active in.

00:32:24.010 --> 00:32:26.290
Can you tell us a little
bit about the activities

00:32:26.290 --> 00:32:30.629
at Northern California
ACLU, taking on that regard?

00:32:30.629 --> 00:32:31.420
ABDI SOLTANI: Yeah.

00:32:31.420 --> 00:32:34.690
So you know, when
you get into reading

00:32:34.690 --> 00:32:37.180
the Constitution and
especially the Bill of Rights,

00:32:37.180 --> 00:32:40.450
the original 10
Amendments, a lot of it

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:43.600
is about the operation of
the criminal justice system.

00:32:43.600 --> 00:32:45.910
The Fourth Amendment
is the right

00:32:45.910 --> 00:32:49.390
to be secure in our persons
from unreasonable search

00:32:49.390 --> 00:32:50.650
and seizure.

00:32:50.650 --> 00:32:53.650
The Fifth Amendment is
a due process provision.

00:32:53.650 --> 00:32:56.110
The Eighth Amendment protects
us from cruel and unusual

00:32:56.110 --> 00:32:57.460
punishment.

00:32:57.460 --> 00:32:59.920
So for an organization
whose mission

00:32:59.920 --> 00:33:03.130
is to provide for and
protect constitutional rights

00:33:03.130 --> 00:33:05.890
for everyone, the
criminal justice system

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:09.400
becomes, by definition, a
central part of the work

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:12.310
that the ACLU does
today and has done

00:33:12.310 --> 00:33:17.440
for the better part of a
century of being in existence.

00:33:17.440 --> 00:33:20.980
Beginning in the
1980s especially,

00:33:20.980 --> 00:33:25.840
the set of policies in the war
on drugs and other policies

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:30.250
really led to this rapid growth
in our criminal justice system,

00:33:30.250 --> 00:33:32.920
what we call mass incarceration.

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:38.530
And that period also marks
a very rapid increase

00:33:38.530 --> 00:33:40.520
in the number of
people of color,

00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:43.570
especially African-Americans,
as well as Latinos,

00:33:43.570 --> 00:33:48.860
being part of that
system of incarceration.

00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:51.080
In the arc of what
we were talking

00:33:51.080 --> 00:33:53.240
about with the 14th
Amendment, there's

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:56.840
a wonderful book written by
Michelle Alexander called

00:33:56.840 --> 00:33:59.450
"The New Jim Crow" that a
lot of people have read.

00:33:59.450 --> 00:34:01.640
It's gotten a lot of attention.

00:34:01.640 --> 00:34:04.970
And Michelle makes the
argument that the system

00:34:04.970 --> 00:34:09.080
of mass incarceration became
the next manifestation

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:12.170
of the previous system
of racial segregation

00:34:12.170 --> 00:34:15.290
that was created after the
period of Reconstruction.

00:34:15.290 --> 00:34:19.010
And this became the
new, legalized way

00:34:19.010 --> 00:34:22.610
in which to promote inequality
after the gains of the Civil

00:34:22.610 --> 00:34:25.100
Rights movement.

00:34:25.100 --> 00:34:28.000
So all of that to say that this
is an incredibly important area

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.199
of work.

00:34:29.199 --> 00:34:34.929
Over the last eight or so years,
the California legislature,

00:34:34.929 --> 00:34:37.600
California voters,
Governor Brown

00:34:37.600 --> 00:34:40.630
have enacted a set of reforms
to reduce the number of people

00:34:40.630 --> 00:34:42.130
incarcerated.

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:44.710
Initially, part of the
pressure was the recession.

00:34:44.710 --> 00:34:47.409
There was pressure to
cut government, state,

00:34:47.409 --> 00:34:48.699
and local government spending.

00:34:48.699 --> 00:34:51.370
And incarceration is
a pretty unwise use

00:34:51.370 --> 00:34:55.380
of resources, especially
the way we've been doing it.

00:34:55.380 --> 00:34:58.340
But it was also prompted partly
by a Supreme Court decision

00:34:58.340 --> 00:35:00.230
in a case called
Plata that dealt

00:35:00.230 --> 00:35:02.480
with the condition of
incarceration in our state

00:35:02.480 --> 00:35:04.250
prisons.

00:35:04.250 --> 00:35:06.590
So right now, today,
there are a couple

00:35:06.590 --> 00:35:08.630
of places where we
really urge people

00:35:08.630 --> 00:35:11.030
to be attentive and involved.

00:35:11.030 --> 00:35:14.690
The first is our
county prosecutors,

00:35:14.690 --> 00:35:17.890
which in California are
called district attorneys,

00:35:17.890 --> 00:35:21.470
they are the most important
actor in the criminal justice

00:35:21.470 --> 00:35:22.890
system.

00:35:22.890 --> 00:35:27.420
When you think about this
problem, 90%, plus or minus

00:35:27.420 --> 00:35:30.930
of incarcerated people are
held either in local government

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:32.730
or state government.

00:35:32.730 --> 00:35:34.620
This problem of
mass incarceration--

00:35:34.620 --> 00:35:37.510
there are federal issues
that are involved,

00:35:37.510 --> 00:35:41.550
but it's very much a
county and a state issue.

00:35:41.550 --> 00:35:46.110
So every person should know
who is your elected district

00:35:46.110 --> 00:35:47.220
attorney.

00:35:47.220 --> 00:35:50.250
If you live in Santa Clara
County, San Mateo County,

00:35:50.250 --> 00:35:52.550
or if you're watching
this anywhere else,

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:54.690
there is someone in
your county government

00:35:54.690 --> 00:35:57.990
who is your representative,
the advocate of the people

00:35:57.990 --> 00:36:00.110
in the criminal justice system.

00:36:00.110 --> 00:36:02.310
And at the ACLU,
we're asking people

00:36:02.310 --> 00:36:04.350
to know who that official is.

00:36:04.350 --> 00:36:07.470
Call that office and ask
them to pursue policies

00:36:07.470 --> 00:36:11.100
that reduce incarceration,
that promote alternatives

00:36:11.100 --> 00:36:13.080
to incarceration.

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:15.630
So that's one major area.

00:36:15.630 --> 00:36:17.890
And I mean, for the
people in the room,

00:36:17.890 --> 00:36:20.280
raise your hand if you know
who your district attorney is

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:23.010
for your county.

00:36:23.010 --> 00:36:25.110
So for the people
watching on the webcast,

00:36:25.110 --> 00:36:27.360
there's a lot of shrugging
and very interesting

00:36:27.360 --> 00:36:30.420
facial expressions that
all say we don't know.

00:36:30.420 --> 00:36:32.760
So I would make that
your assignment today.

00:36:32.760 --> 00:36:36.390
Look up who is your
county district attorney,

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:38.900
and make a phone call
to that office and say,

00:36:38.900 --> 00:36:41.070
I am concerned about
the fact that I

00:36:41.070 --> 00:36:43.080
live in a country
that is the world's

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:44.880
leader in incarceration.

00:36:44.880 --> 00:36:48.540
And I'd like to know what are
the steps your office is taking

00:36:48.540 --> 00:36:51.240
to dramatically reduce the
number of people who are locked

00:36:51.240 --> 00:36:54.780
behind bars, to find
alternatives to incarceration

00:36:54.780 --> 00:36:56.610
for people with mental
health problems,

00:36:56.610 --> 00:37:00.300
or for people who can be
set on a different path.

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:02.610
And then centrally,
what steps are you

00:37:02.610 --> 00:37:05.450
taking to address
racial inequality

00:37:05.450 --> 00:37:10.400
in the decision of who to charge
and what charges to pursue?

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:12.770
I think for any of
us, whether we're

00:37:12.770 --> 00:37:16.370
a citizen or a person
who's not a citizen,

00:37:16.370 --> 00:37:19.850
to abrogate our voice in
our criminal justice system

00:37:19.850 --> 00:37:24.350
and to not hold these people
who are elected accountable

00:37:24.350 --> 00:37:26.960
is giving up part of
our responsibility.

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:31.000
Because they are carrying out
these policies in our name

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:34.960
as the elected representative
of the people in court.

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:37.570
So that's part of our
responsibility to check that

00:37:37.570 --> 00:37:40.240
and to rein it in.

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:43.300
A second big area is bail.

00:37:43.300 --> 00:37:49.430
And I think that that's a space
in which we are very active.

00:37:49.430 --> 00:37:54.620
More than half of the people
who are held in our county jails

00:37:54.620 --> 00:37:58.890
are people who are not yet
found guilty of a crime.

00:37:58.890 --> 00:38:02.340
They've been charged
of a crime, and they're

00:38:02.340 --> 00:38:05.570
being held awaiting trial.

00:38:05.570 --> 00:38:09.350
In the United States, when
you are charged with a crime,

00:38:09.350 --> 00:38:12.670
you have an opportunity
usually to post bail.

00:38:12.670 --> 00:38:15.760
And the Constitution actually
says that there shall not

00:38:15.760 --> 00:38:18.220
be excessive bail.

00:38:18.220 --> 00:38:20.710
But when we live in
a time, in an era,

00:38:20.710 --> 00:38:23.830
where there's so much
economic inequality,

00:38:23.830 --> 00:38:30.370
most Americans cannot handle
like a $400 car emergency,

00:38:30.370 --> 00:38:34.630
let alone have to pay tens of
thousands of dollars in bail

00:38:34.630 --> 00:38:38.260
to await trial outside of jail.

00:38:38.260 --> 00:38:43.750
So what you do is, you post a
bond through a commercial bail

00:38:43.750 --> 00:38:46.610
bond company.

00:38:46.610 --> 00:38:49.250
The commercial bail bond
industry, the way it works

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:54.620
is that, if your bail is, say,
$50,000, the $10,000 of it

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:56.600
is nonrefundable.

00:38:56.600 --> 00:39:00.920
So even if you show up to
court, you don't get that back.

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:05.420
And so for a lot of people, that
then creates this cycle of debt

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:07.520
and contributes to poverty.

00:39:07.520 --> 00:39:11.240
And so even if you're innocent,
even if you meet every court

00:39:11.240 --> 00:39:16.090
date, you're still left
with that economic penalty.

00:39:16.090 --> 00:39:18.820
So replacing bail
requires us to be

00:39:18.820 --> 00:39:21.250
very thoughtful about
what do we replace

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:24.260
the system of
commercial bail with.

00:39:24.260 --> 00:39:26.720
I don't think there's
much to be said in defense

00:39:26.720 --> 00:39:28.550
of commercial money bail.

00:39:28.550 --> 00:39:34.430
It's kind of hard to justify
the idea that a person who

00:39:34.430 --> 00:39:39.080
has money can secure their
freedom through bail,

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:41.720
and a person who
doesn't languishes

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:43.550
in jail awaiting trial.

00:39:43.550 --> 00:39:47.690
It's pretty hard to
defend that system.

00:39:47.690 --> 00:39:50.660
I think we've done a good job
of making the case for why

00:39:50.660 --> 00:39:52.490
we need to make the switch.

00:39:52.490 --> 00:39:54.140
But I think that
the alternative is

00:39:54.140 --> 00:39:56.660
one that needs to be very
carefully thought through

00:39:56.660 --> 00:39:58.890
to be one that
reduces incarceration

00:39:58.890 --> 00:40:00.620
while people await trial.

00:40:00.620 --> 00:40:03.260
And we could talk about that
some more if you'd like.

00:40:03.260 --> 00:40:05.009
AUDIENCE: Didn't the
city of San Francisco

00:40:05.009 --> 00:40:08.990
just pass something that
eliminates the requirement

00:40:08.990 --> 00:40:10.430
of bail, or the--

00:40:10.430 --> 00:40:11.180
ABDI SOLTANI: Yes.

00:40:11.180 --> 00:40:14.780
So it's a great question about
whether San Francisco voted

00:40:14.780 --> 00:40:17.030
to end bail.

00:40:17.030 --> 00:40:21.110
There's a movement around the
country to end commercial bail

00:40:21.110 --> 00:40:25.730
and switch to a system where a
person can receive services, be

00:40:25.730 --> 00:40:28.340
out of jail while
they're awaiting trial.

00:40:28.340 --> 00:40:31.160
With rare exceptions,
if the person poses

00:40:31.160 --> 00:40:35.480
like an imminent threat
to public safety.

00:40:35.480 --> 00:40:41.120
A lot of local jurisdictions
are adopting reforms to bail.

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:43.220
There's another related
issue, which is around

00:40:43.220 --> 00:40:46.610
fines and fees that are
charged to criminal defendants,

00:40:46.610 --> 00:40:48.390
or people who've been in jail.

00:40:48.390 --> 00:40:51.350
And jurisdictions like San
Francisco and Alameda County

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:54.320
are moving in the direction
of eliminating those.

00:40:54.320 --> 00:40:58.730
But California has
not eliminated--

00:40:58.730 --> 00:41:02.300
well, the legislature
just passed a bill, SB10,

00:41:02.300 --> 00:41:06.060
that the ACLU originally
sponsored and supported.

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:09.480
But we ultimately withdrew
our support and opposed it.

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:13.870
What SB10 does is it ends
commercial cash bail.

00:41:13.870 --> 00:41:16.430
But what it created
as an alternative

00:41:16.430 --> 00:41:18.080
creates too much detention.

00:41:18.080 --> 00:41:20.020
There's big categories
of people who

00:41:20.020 --> 00:41:23.480
will be presumed to be
held in jail we just

00:41:23.480 --> 00:41:25.640
felt that that is not the
direction that the bail

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:28.660
reform needs to go.

00:41:28.660 --> 00:41:31.680
