segregation is getting worse

00:41:31.680 --> 00:41:35.070
what do you consider as a
successful long term plan

00:41:35.070 --> 00:41:38.244
to improve the integration?

00:41:38.244 --> 00:41:39.660
ABDI SOLTANI: Wow,
great question.

00:41:39.660 --> 00:41:41.850
That question is from
Anonymous-- good job,

00:41:41.850 --> 00:41:44.010
Anonymous.

00:41:44.010 --> 00:41:47.160
You know, the relationship
of school segregation

00:41:47.160 --> 00:41:52.330
really also goes with housing
and residential segregation.

00:41:52.330 --> 00:41:56.070
So when it comes to actual
segregation in terms

00:41:56.070 --> 00:41:59.280
of schools, after
the Brown versus

00:41:59.280 --> 00:42:02.080
Board of Education
decision in 1954,

00:42:02.080 --> 00:42:08.790
which is as important a
Supreme Court as we have had,

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:11.070
what that said is that
we will not tolerate

00:42:11.070 --> 00:42:13.500
separate and equal schools.

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:15.000
And there was a set
of policies that

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:17.820
went into place to create
integration and provide

00:42:17.820 --> 00:42:21.060
more access to equal
educational opportunities.

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:22.820
Subsequent Supreme
Court decisions

00:42:22.820 --> 00:42:24.990
said that that
responsibility does not

00:42:24.990 --> 00:42:27.180
cross school districts.

00:42:27.180 --> 00:42:30.330
It's only within a
given school district.

00:42:30.330 --> 00:42:34.110
So to the extent that our
neighborhoods and our cities

00:42:34.110 --> 00:42:38.990
are so segregated that people
cannot afford to live anywhere

00:42:38.990 --> 00:42:42.530
in Santa Clara County or Alameda
County because of the cost

00:42:42.530 --> 00:42:46.430
of housing or in the vicinity
of a school district,

00:42:46.430 --> 00:42:50.240
it's very difficult under
current Supreme Court precedent

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:54.410
to create more diverse schools
across those school district

00:42:54.410 --> 00:42:55.670
lines.

00:42:55.670 --> 00:42:57.860
Within a school district,
school districts

00:42:57.860 --> 00:42:59.870
can actually adopt
a number of policies

00:42:59.870 --> 00:43:02.860
to make sure that the
schools are diverse.

00:43:02.860 --> 00:43:04.550
And actually, the
ACLU has had a number

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:07.010
of cases here in California
that tried to do that

00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:09.950
within the bounds of state law.

00:43:09.950 --> 00:43:13.850
There's a Proposition 209, which
eliminated affirmative action

00:43:13.850 --> 00:43:16.340
based on race or
gender, that also

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:18.500
has this negative
effect on the ability

00:43:18.500 --> 00:43:20.050
to create diversity in schools.

00:43:20.050 --> 00:43:24.300
But there's ways to do
it still within the law.

00:43:24.300 --> 00:43:27.330
On education, though, there's
a whole set of other issues

00:43:27.330 --> 00:43:30.990
that deal with access to
adequate funding for low income

00:43:30.990 --> 00:43:33.030
kids and kids of color.

00:43:33.030 --> 00:43:37.590
Also, one of the big issues we
deal with is the significant

00:43:37.590 --> 00:43:41.550
racial inequality in school
suspensions and expulsions,

00:43:41.550 --> 00:43:44.500
where the research shows that
for very similar behavior,

00:43:44.500 --> 00:43:47.850
especially-- the most
extreme is black boys--

00:43:47.850 --> 00:43:50.550
face very harsh
punishment compared

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:52.110
to other kids in the schools.

00:43:52.110 --> 00:43:54.800
So those are a set of
issues around education

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:58.020
in which we're very active.

00:43:58.020 --> 00:43:59.970
AUDIENCE: The preamble
to the First Amendment

00:43:59.970 --> 00:44:02.995
says Congress shall pass
no law, dot, dot, dot.

00:44:02.995 --> 00:44:04.620
And it seems that
there is a great deal

00:44:04.620 --> 00:44:11.010
of misunderstanding in the
populace about that part of it.

00:44:11.010 --> 00:44:14.130
Can you comment on the
legal ramifications

00:44:14.130 --> 00:44:18.600
of, say, the social
media ban of Alex Jones?

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:22.140
ABDI SOLTANI: Yeah, so the
First Amendment, as you said,

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:25.620
does say Congress
shall pass no law.

00:44:25.620 --> 00:44:28.600
And then it goes on
to fill that out.

00:44:28.600 --> 00:44:35.250
So that has been understood to
mean that a mayor, a president,

00:44:35.250 --> 00:44:39.670
a sheriff, a school principal--

00:44:39.670 --> 00:44:41.980
that they can not
unconstitutionally

00:44:41.980 --> 00:44:44.890
violate your freedom
of speech, as well.

00:44:44.890 --> 00:44:48.460
So the Congress shall
pass no law is inclusive

00:44:48.460 --> 00:44:51.410
of other actors in government.

00:44:51.410 --> 00:44:54.100
And actually, it's
the 14th Amendment--

00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:56.950
and part of why
it's so powerful--

00:44:56.950 --> 00:44:58.840
is that it's the
14th Amendment that

00:44:58.840 --> 00:45:00.610
took the rest of
the Bill of Rights

00:45:00.610 --> 00:45:03.640
and applied it to local
and state government.

00:45:03.640 --> 00:45:07.570
Until that time, something
like the First Amendment

00:45:07.570 --> 00:45:10.910
didn't yet apply to
schools or to cities.

00:45:10.910 --> 00:45:14.760
So the 14th Amendment sweeps
in the rest the Constitution

00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:17.110
and applies it to
local government.

00:45:17.110 --> 00:45:20.860
But the First Amendment
itself does not directly

00:45:20.860 --> 00:45:24.100
regulate private conduct.

00:45:24.100 --> 00:45:27.160
The First Amendment
doesn't limit my ability

00:45:27.160 --> 00:45:30.800
to speak to you, and it
has limited applications

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:34.660
when it comes to private
companies or private platforms.

00:45:34.660 --> 00:45:38.470
Even its reach in private
universities is limited.

00:45:38.470 --> 00:45:42.520
So there is some ways in which
the First Amendment is limited.

00:45:42.520 --> 00:45:44.770
But I think the principle
of freedom of expression

00:45:44.770 --> 00:45:47.750
is one that we embrace and want
to apply in as many settings as

00:45:47.750 --> 00:45:48.250
possible.

00:45:53.085 --> 00:45:54.960
AUDIENCE: So next question
on the [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:54.960 --> 00:45:57.760
is that what are
learnings and guidance

00:45:57.760 --> 00:45:59.920
we can take from that
period of Reconstruction

00:45:59.920 --> 00:46:03.160
to launch a movement for
equality and renewed commitment

00:46:03.160 --> 00:46:04.870
to constitutional
rights for all?

00:46:04.870 --> 00:46:08.779
How do we not repeat
elements of history?

00:46:08.779 --> 00:46:10.570
ABDI SOLTANI: So thank
you for the question

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:12.664
about Reconstruction.

00:46:12.664 --> 00:46:14.830
I think for anyone, if you
didn't hear the question,

00:46:14.830 --> 00:46:16.660
it's what are the
lessons we can take

00:46:16.660 --> 00:46:18.400
from the period
of Reconstruction

00:46:18.400 --> 00:46:20.410
that we can apply today?

00:46:20.410 --> 00:46:22.930
And also, how can we make
sure that we don't make

00:46:22.930 --> 00:46:26.480
the same mistakes in the past?

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:29.690
There's some really incredible
books written on this subject.

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:34.220
In the last three years,
I've read more books

00:46:34.220 --> 00:46:36.874
than I think I did
cumulatively in all of college.

00:46:36.874 --> 00:46:38.540
Because I've been
really trying to learn

00:46:38.540 --> 00:46:40.350
about this period
of American history,

00:46:40.350 --> 00:46:44.060
which is full of
important lessons.

00:46:44.060 --> 00:46:47.300
I would say the first and
foremost, the bedrock lesson,

00:46:47.300 --> 00:46:50.760
is the importance of
protecting the right to vote,

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:56.480
but also exercising the right
to vote and running for office.

00:46:56.480 --> 00:46:59.640
The period of Reconstruction,
in just a few short years,

00:46:59.640 --> 00:47:01.910
there were thousands
of African-Americans

00:47:01.910 --> 00:47:06.140
who ran for and were elected to
office throughout the country.

00:47:06.140 --> 00:47:08.690
And I am actually
quite heartened to see

00:47:08.690 --> 00:47:10.730
how much energy there
is right now in both

00:47:10.730 --> 00:47:13.460
protecting voting rights,
but also encouraging people

00:47:13.460 --> 00:47:18.890
to vote and people showing
more energy in that area.

00:47:18.890 --> 00:47:21.340
But the great
warning of the period

00:47:21.340 --> 00:47:23.350
of the end of
Reconstruction is the way

00:47:23.350 --> 00:47:27.790
in which the courts can really
abandon their responsibility

00:47:27.790 --> 00:47:31.270
when it comes to
equality and freedom.

00:47:31.270 --> 00:47:34.270
And that's where it's so
incumbent on all of us

00:47:34.270 --> 00:47:38.030
to-- you know, not all
of us can be a judge.

00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:40.840
And so we have other branches
of government in which

00:47:40.840 --> 00:47:43.270
we can exercise our power.

00:47:43.270 --> 00:47:44.980
And for the people
who are involved

00:47:44.980 --> 00:47:47.560
in the judicial system, it
is so important for them

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:52.710
to uphold the rule of law and
the principles of equality.

00:47:52.710 --> 00:47:54.640
There's a set of
Supreme Court decisions

00:47:54.640 --> 00:47:58.250
that very quickly came
one after the other.

00:47:58.250 --> 00:48:01.370
The most famous is
Plessy versus Ferguson,

00:48:01.370 --> 00:48:06.520
which allowed for explicit
racial discrimination to stand,

00:48:06.520 --> 00:48:09.430
even though we had just
abolished slavery and passed

00:48:09.430 --> 00:48:13.370
these incredible constitutional
amendments and statutes.

00:48:13.370 --> 00:48:15.330
So I would just
say we have to just

00:48:15.330 --> 00:48:20.680
be super alert, super active,
and do everything we can

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:24.380
in every facet of our lives.

00:48:24.380 --> 00:48:26.220
And on that point,
what I would just say

00:48:26.220 --> 00:48:30.910
is we have certain rights and
responsibilities as persons,

00:48:30.910 --> 00:48:32.550
whether we're citizens or not.

00:48:32.550 --> 00:48:34.450
We should use those.

00:48:34.450 --> 00:48:37.260
We have certain rights and
responsibilities as citizens,

00:48:37.260 --> 00:48:39.400
uniquely-- for example,
the right to vote.

00:48:39.400 --> 00:48:41.310
We should use those.

00:48:41.310 --> 00:48:43.140
We also have rights
and responsibilities

00:48:43.140 --> 00:48:45.690
in our companies and
in our associations.

00:48:45.690 --> 00:48:48.890
And so for people
who work in Google,

00:48:48.890 --> 00:48:51.030
you know, your company
has incredible reach,

00:48:51.030 --> 00:48:52.800
incredible power.

00:48:52.800 --> 00:48:54.780
And as you're
looking at the future

00:48:54.780 --> 00:48:57.690
of artificial intelligence,
or the applications

00:48:57.690 --> 00:49:01.590
of your technology, there
are enormous consequences

00:49:01.590 --> 00:49:04.770
for freedom, for
liberty, for equality

00:49:04.770 --> 00:49:07.650
that you, as the stewards
of this technology,

00:49:07.650 --> 00:49:09.090
are actually in
the best position

00:49:09.090 --> 00:49:12.450
to see and address
at the source.

00:49:12.450 --> 00:49:15.720
Ultimately, policymakers and the
public have to weigh in, too.

00:49:15.720 --> 00:49:17.940
But I think you all
have a certain set

00:49:17.940 --> 00:49:20.850
of responsibilities that I
would really encourage you to--

00:49:20.850 --> 00:49:23.970
in many ways, you
already do exercise

00:49:23.970 --> 00:49:25.680
with a great deal
of responsibility.

00:49:25.680 --> 00:49:28.710
And I would really encourage
you to embrace that role

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:32.880
as being that guardian, right at
the source of the code itself,

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:38.278
or as the application or
the idea is being developed.

00:49:38.278 --> 00:49:40.620
AUDIENCE: Question?

00:49:40.620 --> 00:49:43.650
AUDIENCE: So I was wondering,
are there any active efforts

00:49:43.650 --> 00:49:47.330
going on in ACLU to
fight the travel ban?

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:50.280
If yes, what, and if not, why?

00:49:50.280 --> 00:49:52.380
ABDI SOLTANI: OK.

00:49:52.380 --> 00:49:59.490
So the Supreme Court
upheld the Travel Ban 3.0.

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:03.660
And the Supreme Court's
say is the final say

00:50:03.660 --> 00:50:06.660
when it comes to
the judicial system.

00:50:06.660 --> 00:50:08.390
The way in which
we will continue

00:50:08.390 --> 00:50:11.300
to fight the travel
ban, ultimately,

00:50:11.300 --> 00:50:15.050
will be through
legislation in Congress.

00:50:15.050 --> 00:50:17.390
Congress can change that.

00:50:17.390 --> 00:50:21.860
A future president or a future
administration can revoke it,

00:50:21.860 --> 00:50:24.400
can change it.

00:50:24.400 --> 00:50:26.680
Ultimately, there will
also be other cases

00:50:26.680 --> 00:50:28.180
that will go up to the courts.

00:50:28.180 --> 00:50:31.600
So on July 5th, the ACLU
of Northern California

00:50:31.600 --> 00:50:35.800
filed a case on behalf of an
Iranian-American family related

00:50:35.800 --> 00:50:39.550
to how they were being treated
under the waiver provisions,

00:50:39.550 --> 00:50:43.210
or under other provisions
that should be in place.

00:50:43.210 --> 00:50:47.280
So the short answer to your
question is we will not rest,

00:50:47.280 --> 00:50:52.170
and we will not give up, until
this policy of the Executive

00:50:52.170 --> 00:50:54.060
Branch of the United
States government

00:50:54.060 --> 00:50:58.500
is changed and replaced with
a system of immigration that's

00:50:58.500 --> 00:51:03.120
not based on nationality,
or is not based on religion,

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:07.167
or other aspects of protected
human characteristics.

00:51:07.167 --> 00:51:08.625
AUDIENCE: But there
are no active--

00:51:08.625 --> 00:51:11.950
sort of direct
efforts, [INAUDIBLE]??

00:51:11.950 --> 00:51:13.060
ABDI SOLTANI: There are.

00:51:13.060 --> 00:51:16.450
Some of the groups we work with
have brought a class action

00:51:16.450 --> 00:51:20.230
case on the waiver provision.

00:51:20.230 --> 00:51:23.140
But there's not a new
path on litigation

00:51:23.140 --> 00:51:25.780
after the Supreme Court
ruled on the issues

00:51:25.780 --> 00:51:28.930
that the court already ruled on.

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:31.160
But I think that's where
the family separation

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:32.960
issue is so important.

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:36.530
That policy of separating
children from their parents

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:40.300
has many of the same
qualities as the travel ban.

00:51:40.300 --> 00:51:44.720
It's incredibly cruel,
inhumane, and unjust.

00:51:44.720 --> 00:51:48.860
It is motivated by the same
basic prejudice and principle

00:51:48.860 --> 00:51:51.530
of trying to deny that
opportunity for people

00:51:51.530 --> 00:51:54.040
to come to the United States.

00:51:54.040 --> 00:51:56.830
And it also has all of
the same characteristics

00:51:56.830 --> 00:52:00.190
of being completely
irresponsibly conceived

00:52:00.190 --> 00:52:03.670
and executed, such that they
can't even find these children.

00:52:03.670 --> 00:52:07.840
So we may need to move
our fight from one

00:52:07.840 --> 00:52:09.160
arena to another arena.

00:52:09.160 --> 00:52:12.700
But it's all still protecting
that same principle

00:52:12.700 --> 00:52:16.610
of due process and equal
protection under the law.

00:52:16.610 --> 00:52:19.655
And that's where I will
say, as an Iranian-American,

00:52:19.655 --> 00:52:23.710
and as a person who has
earned his citizenship

00:52:23.710 --> 00:52:27.030
because of something
like the 14th Amendment--

00:52:27.030 --> 00:52:29.470
and to the question of
what are the lessons--

00:52:29.470 --> 00:52:33.310
that's where we all have
to pool our resources

00:52:33.310 --> 00:52:37.540
and pool our commitment
not just to protecting

00:52:37.540 --> 00:52:42.310
our individual situation, but
protecting that basic principle

00:52:42.310 --> 00:52:46.540
of equal protection under the
law, due process, and the rule

00:52:46.540 --> 00:52:47.650
of law.

00:52:47.650 --> 00:52:51.910
If those ideas are strong, they
can be strong for all of us.

00:52:51.910 --> 00:52:55.400
But if those ideas become
weak, or if we abandon them

00:52:55.400 --> 00:52:57.370
for one group, it
is the beginning

00:52:57.370 --> 00:52:59.840
of abandoning it for everyone.

00:52:59.840 --> 00:53:04.690
So the rights of women to birth
control, to contraception,

00:53:04.690 --> 00:53:06.100
to abortion--

00:53:06.100 --> 00:53:09.340
that is a fundamental
issue of equality.

00:53:09.340 --> 00:53:11.440
The rights of lesbian
and gay couples

00:53:11.440 --> 00:53:15.280
to love the person that they
love, the right of a person who

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:18.820
is transgender to live their
life free of discrimination

00:53:18.820 --> 00:53:21.770
and to be able to live
their life safely--

00:53:21.770 --> 00:53:24.040
these are issues
that we have to all

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:26.620
be in the circle of protecting
those freedoms and rights,

00:53:26.620 --> 00:53:29.260
because we're all going
to be in it together.

00:53:29.260 --> 00:53:31.840
I think if there's one
lesson from American history,

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:32.720
it's that.

00:53:32.720 --> 00:53:35.050
It's that when we come
together in defense

00:53:35.050 --> 00:53:39.400
of that basic set of commitments
and principles, all of us

00:53:39.400 --> 00:53:42.040
do better, every one of us.

00:53:42.040 --> 00:53:45.100
When that right starts to
be weakened or abandoned,

00:53:45.100 --> 00:53:49.090
then it starts to take it away
from every single one of us.

00:53:49.090 --> 00:53:52.510
So to your great question,
I would say we will persist.

00:53:52.510 --> 00:53:54.670
And we'll find every
possible avenue

00:53:54.670 --> 00:53:57.220
to address the issue
of the Muslim ban.

00:53:57.220 --> 00:53:59.890
But the way we will all do
that is by working together

00:53:59.890 --> 00:54:01.205
on the whole package.

00:54:01.205 --> 00:54:04.750
AUDIENCE: In addition to the
